      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A piercing shriek, especially when starting to move, often suggests that the ceramic or metallic compounds on the new pads are interacting with the rotor in a high-frequency manner. Sometimes, the manufacturer's \"break-in\" procedure is skipped, which is supposed to bed the new pad material against the rotor surface. You might also want to inspect the brake rotor for any glaze or minor warping, which can amplify high-pitched noises. Remember that some modern pads are designed to squeak slightly during the initial bedding phase.",
      "source": "target",
